So, this might be a question for <@U286Q175Y> or <@U28TLDP0R> as they are number guys, but I am trying to make a point about probability of drawing into a combo, so I was going to use the hyper geometric calculator that the cool kids use. So when I use this thing, I plug size of pop, sure, number of successes, and sample size and number for succeeding from sample. I understand that if we are just looking for 1 card in edh wth just opening hand we do 99, 1, 7, 1. But now I want find a secondary card, where that card can be one in about 5. This is where I am getting lost, how do I find the probability now, where it is the first card AND one of 5 in the sample size?
I love problems like these
but I need to absorb a bit more coffee and reread
Sure

your wording makes me a little unsure if you're trying to find [a] the probability of getting the first combo piece (5 in deck) or [b] the probability of getting the first combo piece (1 in deck) and the second combo piece (5 in deck)
B,
ah ok, so that's conditional probability
first you take the probability of getting the first piece: the 99, 1, 7, 1
then you multiply that by the probability of getting the second piece, under the conditions that the first piece was found
so normally the second part would be 99, 5, 7, 1
but since one of the cards is the first combo piece, it's 98, 5, 6, 1
although, you don't really mind if number of successes = 2 or 3 (e.g. you get redundant copies of piece #2)
so you'd want to sum the 2nd combo piece probabilities before multiplying by 1st combo piece probability
Ok, I figured the first part of this, but I knew I was going to miss some parts towards the end
The sum would just be the percentiles of piece 2 for successes = [1,2,3,4,5] added straight up?
